author: @sanchit8818
text: Just wanted to add the difference between \; and +. Basically when you use a + sign, it is like xargs, i.e. "chmod file1, file2, file3". On the other hand \; means you want to loop over each file like "chmod file1; chmod file2; "chmod file3;". Most of the time you can use them interchangeably though as most unix commands like chmod accept multiple files in input.

text: There is a difference between the {} and + sign:  {} Is a placeholder for the result found by find + All result lines are concatenated and the command is executed only a single time with all found results as a parameter  You can check this Yourself by using find with ls -lh ...

text: In case anyone curious, by changing semicolon (;) to plus (+) in   -exec rm  {}  ';' make the command efficient since by doing so command (in this example rm) run only once .
